{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658327","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658327"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:46:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:46:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20726"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20726","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20726"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0,0.13,0.35,0.52]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13602"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95824"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13602","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13602"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20726"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78603"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"7625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11578"},{"type":"tags","id":"11742"},{"type":"tags","id":"11743"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32706"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32707"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95824","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/95824"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EWhen proteins fail to fold correctly in the endoplasmic reticulum, cellular mechanisms must respond to maintain normal function.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the cellular response to an excessive accumulation of misfolded proteins in the endoplasmic reticulum?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increased protein synthesis to compensate for misfolded proteins","Expansion of smooth endoplasmic reticulum only","Immediate induction of autophagy without prior adaptive responses","Transfer of misfolded proteins to the Golgi apparatus for repair","Activation of the unfolded protein response"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eactivation of the unfolded protein response\u003C/strong\u003E (UPR) is triggered when misfolded proteins accumulate in the endoplasmic reticulum (ER). The UPR has three main effects:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EReduction in overall protein synthesis to decrease ER workload\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EIncreased production of chaperone proteins to assist with protein folding\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EEnhanced protein degradation capacity\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect responses are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased protein synthesis to compensate for misfolded proteins\u003C/strong\u003E would worsen ER stress by adding more proteins to an already overwhelmed system\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExpansion of smooth endoplasmic reticulum only\u003C/strong\u003E is not a specific response to protein misfolding, as protein synthesis occurs in the rough ER\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate induction of autophagy without prior adaptive responses\u003C/strong\u003E may occur if ER stress is prolonged but is not the initial response\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransfer of misfolded proteins to the Golgi apparatus for repair\u003C/strong\u003E does not occur - misfolded proteins are retained in the ER\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf the UPR fails to restore normal ER function, persistent activation can lead to cell death through apoptosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The endoplasmic reticulum (ER) is where transmembrane proteins and secretory proteins are synthesised and folded.","The unfolded protein response (UPR) is activated when misfolded proteins accumulate in the ER.","The UPR reduces general protein synthesis while increasing chaperone protein production to restore normal ER function."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 1, The Cell as a Unit of Health and Disease;  p. 13"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78603"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20726"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78603","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/78603"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-29T20:52:46+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-29T20:54:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13602"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95824"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"7625","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7625"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Endoplasmic reticulum","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-31T13:16:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T13:16:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11578","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11578"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"The cell as a unit of health and disease","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":0,"createdAt":"2025-02-26T15:05:04+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-26T15:05:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"18"}},"heading":{"data":